ategically.\n- A segment can contribute 69% of revenue while being operationally independent (e.g., if it purchased launches on the open market).\n- It measures output composition, not input dependency.\n\n**Why the Starship R&D / Connectivity capex metric is superior:**\n\n1. **It captures the disclosed operational bottleneck.** The S-1 explicitly states that Falcon 9 **cannot deploy V3 or V2 Mobile satellites** — only Starship can. V3 satellites deliver a **20x increase in downlink capacity per launch** versus Falcon 9. Without Starship maturing, Connectivity\'s entire next-generation capacity expansion stalls. This metric quantifies the capital relationship between the enabler (Starship R&D) and the enabled (Connectivity capex).\n\n2. **It reflects the capital-allocation linkage.** The filing discloses that intersegment launches are not recognized as revenue; instead, launch costs are capitalized as assets on the receiving segment\'s balance sheet. This means the true "cost" of Connectivity\'s growth runs partly through Space segment R&D, a dependency invisible in the revenue-mix metric but partially visible in the R&D/capex comparison.\n\n3. **It highlights a deteriorating ratio as a risk signal.** As Starship R&D accelerates ($930M/quarter in Q1 2026 vs. $751M average in FY2025), and as Connectivity capex continues to grow (from $2,455M → $3,498M → $4,178M over FY2023–FY2025), the two capital streams are growing in tandem — reflecting the co-dependency but also the increasing scale of capital at risk if Starship development stalls.\n\n**However, neither metric perfectly captures cross-segment dependency.** A more complete measure would involve:\n- The dollar value of intersegment launches (capitalized, not expensed)\n- Starship launch cadence assumptions embedded in Connectivity\'s capacity forecasts\n- The percentage of Connectivity\'s new satellite capacity that *requires* Starship vs. can be served by Falcon 9\n\nThe filing does not fully disclose these gran